post_text: Welcome back RVC Schools! We are so excited to see all of our amazing staff and students. Yesterday marked the first day of a different but GREAT school year. Our students started the day with a quick temperature check before entering the buildings and greeting their teachers and friends. 6ft markers have been placed on the floor of each building to help guide students throughout the day. Students learned proper hand washing and hand sanitizing protocols and were taught how to properly remove a face mask for a mask break. Our Elementary students had a fun first day learning while being protected behind desk guards. Our middle school students worked collaboratively with their remote learning friends. This year will be a bit different, but we will have another great school year here at Rockville Centre Schools.

post_text: South Side High School is proud to announce and congratulate the following seniors on their acceptance not only into their prospective colleges and universities, but for being accepted as an athlete at the college level as well. They will truly be missed in RVC! Ms. Roseto would like to congratulate all of South Side’s 2020 senior student-athletes and wishes them nothing but the best in their futures. She commends them, especially the spring seniors who didn’t get a chance to shine, for their perseverance and understanding during this unprecedented time. She thanks them for their dedication to the Cyclone athletic program and wants them to know that they will be missed.

post_text: Submerged Story Telling was brought to students through the Wilson Elementary School PTA Arts In Motion Committee. During a five-day arts-in-education residency where students learned a range of academic and life skills. Students interact with and explore The Realm to draw conclusions about the story's characters, plot, and themes. Our handcrafted, multi-sensory materials turn the Realm into a differentiated teaching tool that motivates students through entertainment, interaction, and exploration.

post_text: In honor of Black History Month, Robert Ryland, the first black professional tennis player, visited Covert Elementary School! Covert students learned how Bob broke the color barrier in 1944 by being one of the first two black players to compete in the NCAA Championships. Students at Covert were able to meet and greet Bob Ryland, and ask questions about his life.

post_text: Welcome to the Core Coffee Cart where each cup of coffee is brewed with love and life skill! Students in the Core program work hard every day to be sure the South Side Middle School Core Coffee Cart is fully stocked with drinks and snacks for faculty and staff. Students in the Core program are involved in handling all aspects of the coffee cart, such as giving back the proper amount of change, stocking and replenishing snacks, set up and break down and managing the Core Coffee Cart Loyalty Card Program. Each coffee sleeve has been decorated with a personalized message to spread positivity throughout SSMS.

post_text: On Monday morning, Wilson Elementary School 3rd grader Jack Briody received a phone call from NFL Champion Trent Dilfer who called to congratulate him being the grand prize winner of Panini America’s Super Bowl LIV Kid Reporter Contest where more than 100,000 kids participated. To enter the contest, Jack showed off his great writing skills by scripting interview questions that he would ask the athletes. Jack and his family will attend the Pro Football Hall of Fame Merlin Olsen Luncheon and the Panini Pop Warner Skills Clinic. Jack will also be in attendance for Super Bowl LIV, where he’ll be rooting for Mahomes, Tyreek Hill and the Chiefs. Jacks teacher, Mrs. Rinn, along with Principal Duffy and the rest of the school and District are proud of Jack for this wonderful accomplishment!

post_text: Today at South Side Middle School, Students came together with an action plan to contribute to saving Australia’s wildlife. With the help of SSMS teachers, Kori Miller and Jamie Ambruzzo, students showed support by raising money for the thousands of animals suffering. Students donated money and wore animal print or South Side attire. The money will be donated to World Wildlife Fund Australia. The goal is to raise enough money to adopt a Koala and supply it with proper care. Many parts of Australia have been battling wildfires since November and students are passionate about helping. Tune into News12 today at 5:00 PM to see SSMS in action, fundraising for a great cause!

post_text: Watson students learned the principles of social and emotional learning with Beth and Scott Bierko, a dynamic duo that educates the importance of getting along with others. As part of Watson’s year long theme of “Soaring to New Heights,” students learned “The Golden Rule” and “Do the Right Thing” through song, dance and storytelling. Beth and Scott’s performance focused on topics such as dealing with peer pressure, bullying, and strategies to utilize when dealing anger or sadness. Thank you to the Rockville Centre Education Foundation for funding this important social emotional learning experience.

post_text: Covert's FUN RUN fundraiser is coming up this Friday and last week the two classes who had averaged the most funds raised by Friday morning got to duct tape Mr. Raymar and Mr. Figaro to chairs in the cafeteria during lunch. post_text: Visit Riverside Elementary School's Facebook page to see what Mrs. Brooks is doing with crayfish!
shared_text:
Riverside Elementary School
September 23, 2019 at 3:40 PM ·

Mrs. Brooks’ Fourth grade class received live crayfish to observe as part of their Next Generation Science Curriculum this week at Riverside School. Students will be conducting experiments that test what crayfish eat and if they can detect the presence of food in water, as well as how they react to external stimuli. The students observed what they arrived in, and how to put them in their new environment within the classroom. Today, students created a list of rules for the Humane Treatment of the crayfish and will also experiment with food coloring to observe a crayfish breathing under water. All of these observations will help students generate ideas for their upcoming writing piece titled
“A Memoir of a Crayfish”. This will be written from the perspective of a crayfish. We can’t wait to hear more about this exciting learning opportunity for our students and witness their writing come to life after the unit of study is complete.
text:
Visit Riverside Elementary School's Facebook page to see what Mrs. Brooks is doing with crayfish!

Riverside Elementary School
September 23, 2019 at 3:40 PM ·

Mrs. Brooks’ Fourth grade class received live crayfish to observe as part of their Next Generation Science Curriculum this week at Riverside School. Students will be conducting experiments that test what crayfish eat and if they can detect the presence of food in water, as well as how they react to external stimuli. The students observed what they arrived in, and how to put them in their new environment within the classroom. Today, students created a list of rules for the Humane Treatment of the crayfish and will also experiment with food coloring to observe a crayfish breathing under water. All of these observations will help students generate ideas for their upcoming writing piece titled
“A Memoir of a Crayfish”. This will be written from the perspective of a crayfish. We can’t wait to hear more about this exciting learning opportunity for our students and witness their writing come to life after the unit of study is complete.
